00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:45.320
OK, so what about
Lean and Six Sigma?

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:47.693
They're very interrelated.

00:07:47.693 --> 00:07:49.610
They came from somewhat
different backgrounds.

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:51.350
Six Sigma was
developed by Motorola

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:55.880
in the 1980s when they decided
that the big problem they had

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:59.220
was that all their processes
had too much variation.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.195
So, when they built
something, they

00:08:01.195 --> 00:08:03.070
weren't sure what the
output was going to be.

00:08:03.070 --> 00:08:05.690
And so they didn't have very
good what you might call yield.

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:08.540
They had a lot of scrap
and not just in production,

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:11.540
but in office processes
and everything.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:15.130
So Motorola focused on reducing
the variation of every process

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:18.970
so that every process would
have a predictable output

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:20.930
to deliver value
to their customers.

00:08:20.930 --> 00:08:24.300
It was very problem
focused, and the assumption

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:25.420
is you've got a--

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:26.700
that a process isn't working.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.850
So you go, and you do a very
kind of quantitative analysis

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:33.360
and fix that process and
get the variation down.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.150
Lean has the same end
objective of delivering value

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.789
to the customer,
but its focus is

00:08:38.789 --> 00:08:41.370
to reduce waste, to get all
the waste out of the system.

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:43.289
And we'll find out that
most of the thing--

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:46.290
most of the inefficiency
is not the people.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:50.760
It's the system in which the
people are working is wasteful.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:53.500
And it's focused on
keeping everything flowing.

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:56.280
And so the assumption is that
waste removal will improve

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:59.010
businesses and that many
small improvements are

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:00.510
better than a big, giant step.

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:04.350
So lean is very much a process
of starting where you are,

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:06.720
taking whatever system
you have, making

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:09.300
it a little bit better or a
lot better, and then making it

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:11.190
a lot better and then
making it a lot better

00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:12.940
and just continually
trying to improve it.

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:14.190
And that's why it's a journey.

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:23.950
Now, what's happened over the
past 10, 15 years is that--

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:25.917
well, let me back up
and say, 15 years ago,

00:09:25.917 --> 00:09:28.000
there were people saying,
oh, I'm doing Six Sigma,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.410
or I'm doing lean.

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:31.240
It was like there
were two camps.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:34.440
And, luckily, eventually
we got past that,

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:38.890
and most organizations
now pick some portions

00:09:38.890 --> 00:09:43.790
of lean, some portions of Six
Sigma, and bring them together.

00:09:43.790 --> 00:09:47.120
We think of lean as sort
of optimizing flow and Six

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:49.520
Sigma as reducing variation.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.370
And the body of knowledges
have come together

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:54.620
into something that's generally
called Lean Six Sigma.

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:57.440
There are books you can
buy called Lean Six Sigma.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:00.140
And what happens
is an enterprise

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.810
will look at these principles.

00:10:03.810 --> 00:10:06.720
They will tailor their
own version of it.

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:08.790
They will name it and brand it.

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:12.570
And it becomes their operating
strategy or their improvement

00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:13.710
strategy.

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:16.270
So Textron calls theirs
Textron Six Sigma.

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:19.500
Virginia Mason Medical Center
calls it the Virginia Mason

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:20.860
Production System.

00:10:20.860 --> 00:10:22.678
Some of you are
either going to work

00:10:22.678 --> 00:10:23.970
or have been working at Boeing.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:26.640
They call theirs Lean+ now.

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:29.032
And I was talking with
Susan a little earlier.

00:10:29.032 --> 00:10:30.990
Dartmouth, which is a
real leader in this area,

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:33.180
doesn't even call
it lean at all.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.360
And that doesn't matter.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:38.400
It's that the organization
understands their process

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:41.340
improvement and identifies with
it and takes ownership of it

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:44.880
and doesn't get hung
up on what the name is.

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:48.210
So our course is going to
