Nobody, right?

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:23.520
That's what lean is about.

00:23:23.520 --> 00:23:26.310
OK, lean is about
doing simple things

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:27.570
to improve your workplace.

00:23:27.570 --> 00:23:30.300
When I toured the Sikorsky plant
where they make the Black Hawk

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:33.780
helicopter, the plant
manager said, Earll, lean

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:37.420
is the focused application
of common sense.

00:23:37.420 --> 00:23:41.290
This is not complicated stuff.

00:23:41.290 --> 00:23:44.440
And lean is not about making
the worker work harder.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:48.280
Lean is about putting the
worker in an environment where

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:50.910
they can be more
productive and happier.

00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:53.320
OK, so this is
what lean is about.

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:58.420
Most organizations start
with 5S as their first thing.

00:23:58.420 --> 00:23:59.860
And let me just share--

00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:01.860
just to underline it,
I'll share you an example.

00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:04.560
So I live in the small
town of 9,000 people.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:06.360
The whole county only
has 30,000 people.

00:24:06.360 --> 00:24:07.860
It's a rural community.

00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:10.535
Our hospital started
adopting lean.

00:24:10.535 --> 00:24:11.910
The very first
thing they did was

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:15.210
they went into the hospital
laundry and applied 5S.

00:24:15.210 --> 00:24:17.380
The laundry was
so dysfunctional.

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:19.590
They had high
turnover of employees.

00:24:19.590 --> 00:24:22.530
The linens and gowns
were not on the floors

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:23.490
when they needed to be.

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:27.030
The laundry bin, they didn't get
to the bottom of it each day,

00:24:27.030 --> 00:24:27.780
the dirty laundry.

00:24:27.780 --> 00:24:30.240
So, the next day, more
laundry was on top and so on.

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:35.240
In one week, the women in the
laundry who operate the laundry

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:37.850
took 5S with a
facilitator and a coach.

00:24:37.850 --> 00:24:39.950
They reorganized their laundry.

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:43.970
And it went from
that to now they get

00:24:43.970 --> 00:24:45.410
all the laundry done every day.

00:24:45.410 --> 00:24:46.493
I've been in this laundry.

00:24:46.493 --> 00:24:47.857
The women are so happy.

00:24:47.857 --> 00:24:49.940
They just can't-- they
just want to tell you about

00:24:49.940 --> 00:24:51.140
their workplace.

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:53.780
They've had no turnover
since they did this.

00:24:53.780 --> 00:24:56.300
And everybody in the hospital
is affected by the laundry.

00:24:56.300 --> 00:24:58.620
And they all knew
it was a success.

00:24:58.620 --> 00:25:00.350
So, if you want to
start in a hospital,

00:25:00.350 --> 00:25:04.230
start in the laundry with 5S.

00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:07.700
The last S is to sustain,
often the hardest part.

00:25:07.700 --> 00:25:12.030
I like the Virginia Mason
version of it, self-discipline.

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:15.830
Sustainment should be-- the trap
as you do this one-week event

00:25:15.830 --> 00:25:18.070
like I mentioned in
the laundry, and then

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:19.440
you drift back into old habits.

00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:23.090
So the hard part is
keeping this as a mindset.

00:25:23.090 --> 00:25:24.590
Sometimes, you have
to have a chart,

00:25:24.590 --> 00:25:27.510
but usually you should
just be able to do it.

00:25:27.510 --> 00:25:31.150
OK, so that's your
first lean experience.

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:35.617
Let's now talk about why lean
is being applied in these areas.

00:25:35.617 --> 00:25:37.700
OK, we're going to look
at aerospace, health here.

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:39.610
And we're to look also
at New Balance shoes

00:25:39.610 --> 00:25:40.793
just for three comparisons.

00:25:40.793 --> 00:25:42.710
So aerospace is a really
interesting industry.

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:45.693
It's a flagship industry
of the United States.

00:25:45.693 --> 00:25:47.110
It's one of these
things that goes

00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:48.820
with the image of the country.

00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:50.770
It enables the movement
of people and goods.

00:25:53.710 --> 00:25:56.400
It enables communication.

00:25:56.400 --> 00:25:59.150
It's critical to
national security.

00:25:59.150 --> 00:26:02.110
And it's a source of
inspiration for many people

00:26:02.110 --> 00:26:03.880
for exploration.

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:07.930
Now, why did aerospace
turn to adopting lean?

00:26:07.930 --> 00:26:12.750
Here's an industry where we
think we're the world's leader.

00:26:12.750 --> 00:26:15.063
And I pause because we may
not be, but we think we are.

00:26:15.063 --> 00:26:16.230
But why did we turn to lean?

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:18.860
Well, here's why.

00:26:18.860 --> 00:26:21.200
This is a study that came
out of the Sloan School

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:23.960
by Jim Utterback that shows
the natural progression

00:26:23.960 --> 00:26:27.070
of many different
industries plotted

00:26:27.070 --> 00:26:30.032
by the number of companies
in a particular industry.

00:26:30.032 --> 00:26:31.490
So this is the
typewriter industry.

00:26:31.490 --> 00:26:35.320
So it started in the late
1870s, and companies came in.

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:37.330
They reached a peak
of about 80 companies.

00:26:37.330 --> 00:26:40.150
And then somewhere they
reached a peak around 1910.

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:42.310
And then the number of
companies started declining.

00:26:42.310 --> 00:26:45.880
And, of course, there's probably
no typewriter companies now.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:46.450
What happens?

00:26:46.450 --> 00:26:49.900
Well, this phase, this is
where the product architecture

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:52.180
and product characteristics
are not set.

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:55.240
So many inventors come up
with new ways of doing things.

00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:58.570
Eventually, somehow,
the best design emerges.

00:26:58.570 --> 00:27:01.450
And that's where the
market consolidates around.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:04.000
And then, instead, there's
not really real opportunities

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:04.750
for new companies.

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:07.720
What happens is companies buy
up other companies that emerge.

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:09.160
And, at this point,
it's very hard

00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:10.810
to change the
product architecture.

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:15.432
This keyboard we all use
came out of this era.

00:27:15.432 --> 00:27:17.890
It's pretty well known that
there's more efficient keyboard

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:22.300
layouts, but it's impossible
to change that now.

00:27:22.300 --> 00:27:24.910
It's impossible to change it
because it's the standard.

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:28.810
OK, here's the automobile
industry, same kind of thing

00:27:28.810 --> 00:27:29.540
here.

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:33.790
The main product architecture
was the enclosed steel body.

00:27:33.790 --> 00:27:34.990
Here's aerospace.

00:27:34.990 --> 00:27:37.195
Now, this is
representative aerospace.

00:27:37.195 --> 00:27:40.240
So it's probably-- it's just
some of the major companies,

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:43.600
but, throughout the
1900s up to about 1960,

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:45.790
we had a growth of the
number of companies.

00:27:45.790 --> 00:27:51.610
Then along came something
that looks like a 747, 707,

00:27:51.610 --> 00:27:52.390
and other things.

00:27:52.390 --> 00:27:54.650
And we sort of reached
the product architecture.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:58.420
And then we would have gone on
this decline just as companies.

00:27:58.420 --> 00:28:01.420
But we get to this point
here, and there's a plateau.

00:28:01.420 --> 00:28:03.610
We're in the Cold War.

00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:05.930
And the government,
for strategic reasons,

00:28:05.930 --> 00:28:07.540
wanted to keep a
big industrial base.

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:10.150
So they invested in
that industrial base.

00:28:10.150 --> 00:28:13.450
When the Cold War was over,
the Secretary of Defense

00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:16.280
invited all the CEOs of the
major aerospace companies

00:28:16.280 --> 00:28:16.780
to dinner.

00:28:16.780 --> 00:28:18.310
It's called "The Last Supper."

00:28:18.310 --> 00:28:21.623
And he said, we don't
need this many companies.

00:28:21.623 --> 00:28:24.040
And so we're not going to have
as many, but it's up to you

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:24.830
to sort it out.

00:28:24.830 --> 00:28:26.413
We'll let the
marketplace sort it out.

00:28:26.413 --> 00:28:31.310
So Boeing buys McDonnell
Douglas, so on, and so forth.

00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:34.340
And we have now consolidation
and fewer aerospace companies.

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:38.110
Had we not had the Cold War, we
probably would have done this.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:43.870
But here's where aerospace--
here's where LAI started.

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:48.520
We had an industry,
which was inefficient

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:51.610
and couldn't survive
in the new world.

00:28:51.610 --> 00:28:54.300
And so they turned to lean.

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:55.902
So we had a company with--

00:28:55.902 --> 00:28:57.360
companies that have
mature products

00:28:57.360 --> 00:28:59.310
can't survive on a
business strategy that's

00:28:59.310 --> 00:29:02.720
designed for early growth.

00:29:02.720 --> 00:29:04.820
Here's one of the
things that happens.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:06.635
In an early phase,
when there's not--

00:29:06.635 --> 00:29:08.510
when the competition
really hasn't developed,

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:10.790
you can charge what you want.

00:29:10.790 --> 00:29:14.630
You can charge what you
want for a new device.

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:16.280
And then you
subtract your costs,

00:29:16.280 --> 00:29:18.050
and you get whatever profit.

00:29:18.050 --> 00:29:20.570
Competition builds
up, or the government

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:23.733
says we're not going to pay
as much for airplanes anymore.

00:29:23.733 --> 00:29:26.810
OK, the customer sets the price.

00:29:26.810 --> 00:29:30.680
The only way for you to make a
profit is to reduce your costs.

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:33.500
So you have to become
more efficient.

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:36.723
It's just the way it is,
or you don't survive.

00:29:36.723 --> 00:29:39.140
Here's an example of some of
the problems in the aerospace

00:29:39.140 --> 00:29:40.760
industry.

00:29:40.760 --> 00:29:42.500
Here are three programs--

00:29:42.500 --> 00:29:44.750
the second block of
the GPS satellites,

00:29:44.750 --> 00:29:47.960
the Joint Strike
Fighter, Boeing 787.

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:51.760
These are new airplanes, years
behind schedule, one, two,

00:29:51.760 --> 00:29:57.590
three, four, billion
dollars overrun, $12 billion

00:29:57.590 --> 00:30:00.470
beyond the development costs.

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:03.650
The price per unit, they're
going to buy a lot of F-35's.

00:30:03.650 --> 00:30:07.220
The price has doubled,
and it's still in trouble.

00:30:07.220 --> 00:30:09.680
Other programs where their
costs and schedule is overrun is

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:11.450
the F-22 and so on, the A340--

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:13.940
A380, so on.

00:30:13.940 --> 00:30:17.510
This is what's called
the burning platform.

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:19.340
The paradigm here
is people adopt lean

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:21.420
when the platform they're
staying on is burning.

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:24.830
And, if they don't do something,
they're going to disappear.

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:26.990
Now, there are so many
aerospace programs

00:30:26.990 --> 00:30:29.600
which are executed very well.

00:30:29.600 --> 00:30:31.760
And we've learned a lot
from studying those.

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:34.100
So I don't want to say the
aerospace can't do anything,

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:36.750
but there are a lot of problems
with the aerospace programs.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:40.840
Health care, there was a
book published in 2003 called

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:42.553
Crossing the Quality Chasm.

00:30:42.553 --> 00:30:44.470
It was published by the
Institute of Medicine.

00:30:44.470 --> 00:30:47.470
And the paradigm here
was this is the health

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:48.910
care we're delivering.

00:30:48.910 --> 00:30:51.580
This is the health care
we know how to deliver.

00:30:51.580 --> 00:30:55.688
And there's such a wide gap
in quality of health care

00:30:55.688 --> 00:30:57.730
that we have a big chasm
between what we're doing

00:30:57.730 --> 00:30:59.530
and what we should be doing.

00:30:59.530 --> 00:31:02.250
And they outlined what the
objectives of health care are

00:31:02.250 --> 00:31:03.720
and that these are not new aims.

00:31:03.720 --> 00:31:06.312
These are aims that have
been there for many years.

00:31:06.312 --> 00:31:07.770
And most people go
into health care

00:31:07.770 --> 00:31:10.582
because they want to do this.

00:31:10.582 --> 00:31:12.540
Probably, all of you guys
are going into health

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:13.748
care because you don't want--

00:31:13.748 --> 00:31:15.582
you probably didn't say
I picked health care

00:31:15.582 --> 00:31:17.850
because it's an inefficient
system that I can work in.

00:31:17.850 --> 00:31:19.475
You picked health
care because you want

00:31:19.475 --> 00:31:20.950
to help people and do things.

00:31:20.950 --> 00:31:23.490
So we need to do that.

00:31:23.490 --> 00:31:24.690
OK, but what are some signs?

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:28.710
Well, I think we've all heard
about the cost of health care.

00:31:28.710 --> 00:31:30.713
There are different
metrics here.

00:31:30.713 --> 00:31:32.880
I don't think we have to
go through those in detail.

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:34.330
There are quality issues.

00:31:34.330 --> 00:31:36.100
This is the one that
was staggering to me,

00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:40.410
the study done in 1999
that between about 50,000

00:31:40.410 --> 00:31:42.750
and 100,000 people a
year in our country

00:31:42.750 --> 00:31:46.680
die from perfectly
preventable medical mistakes.

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:50.940
OK, that's more people
than die on the highway.

00:31:50.940 --> 00:31:53.560
And, by the way, that number
still has not changed too much.

00:31:53.560 --> 00:31:55.920
It's gotten a little bit
better maybe, but not changed.

00:31:55.920 --> 00:31:59.497
Many people don't have
access to health care.

00:31:59.497 --> 00:32:01.080
This slide is a
little bit out of date

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:04.540
because of the Affordable
Health Care Act.

00:32:04.540 --> 00:32:08.565
And 60% of the
doctors in the survey

00:32:08.565 --> 00:32:10.690
said they wouldn't recommend
going into health care

00:32:10.690 --> 00:32:12.490
to their children.

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:14.970
Here we've got Bo is an
emergency doctor, emergency

00:32:14.970 --> 00:32:15.790
medicine doctor.

00:32:15.790 --> 00:32:19.140
Is 50% of your time
spent on paperwork?

00:32:19.140 --> 00:32:20.648
AUDIENCE: On waste
on a good day.

00:32:20.648 --> 00:32:22.440
EARLL MURMAN: On a good
day, 50% is wasted.

00:32:22.440 --> 00:32:25.080
And Susan is a nurse.

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:27.600
Many studies have shown we
have a big shortage of nurses

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:28.740
coming up here.

00:32:28.740 --> 00:32:32.310
OK, so we've got some problems,
as you all know about.

00:32:32.310 --> 00:32:34.140
So, basically, what
we say in health care

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:35.430
is there's a value crisis.

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:37.710
Value is defined
as what you deliver

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:39.930
and divided by what you pay for.

00:32:39.930 --> 00:32:42.720
And roughly about
half the health care

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:45.870
we know how to deliver to
the patient gets delivered.

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:50.610
And the cost, this is of GDP.

00:32:50.610 --> 00:32:54.155
In 2007, we were spending 16%
of our gross domestic product

00:32:54.155 --> 00:32:54.780
on health care.

00:32:54.780 --> 00:32:57.330
In 2050, it's
supposed to be 37%.

00:32:57.330 --> 00:33:01.260
That's just unsustainable
and the same with Medicare.

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:03.780
So we hope that
lean thinking can

00:33:03.780 --> 00:33:06.490
be one piece of a puzzle
of improving health care.

00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:09.360
It's a complicated--
it's a complicated field.

00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:13.110
And there's no simple
solution, but lean can help.

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:15.000
OK, so those are
two industries as

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:16.250
to why they're applying lean.

00:33:16.250 --> 00:33:17.670
Now, let's talk a
little bit about what

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:19.378
is an enterprise
because, in this course,

00:33:19.378 --> 00:33:22.840
we very much focus on applying
lean across an enterprise,

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:27.010
not just a manufacturing
or a clinic thing.

00:33:27.010 --> 00:33:29.980
So an enterprise
is broadly defined

00:33:29.980 --> 00:33:31.630
as one or more
organizations having

00:33:31.630 --> 00:33:34.060
related activities,
a unified operation,

00:33:34.060 --> 00:33:36.740
and a common business purpose.

00:33:36.740 --> 00:33:40.030
And so you might have, in
an engineering enterprise,

00:33:40.030 --> 00:33:44.360
customers, engineering
products, product development

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:48.140
or engineering, manufacturing,
suppliers, finance, and so on

00:33:48.140 --> 00:33:50.640
and support.

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:53.740
And enterprises can
be pretty complex.

00:33:53.740 --> 00:33:57.040
So it's hard to define the
boundaries in an enterprise.

00:33:57.040 --> 00:33:58.530
It's somewhat contextual.

00:33:58.530 --> 00:34:04.240
You might draw it around your
table here as an enterprise,

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:07.180
but most enterprises
have partners

00:34:07.180 --> 00:34:11.580
that they have close
operating agreements with.

00:34:11.580 --> 00:34:16.429
And so we call the core
enterprise the organization

00:34:16.429 --> 00:34:24.170
plus its most closely related
partners that work with them.

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:26.540
And then, beyond that, there's
an extended enterprise,

00:34:26.540 --> 00:34:31.570
which is all their suppliers and
actually their customers too.

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:35.600
And also their community and
regulatory agencies and things

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:38.929
like that all can
affect their enterprise.

00:34:38.929 --> 00:34:46.370
So a company like Boeing
has maybe 2,000 suppliers.

00:34:46.370 --> 00:34:47.989
And, by the way,
those 2,000 suppliers

00:34:47.989 --> 00:34:51.290
are suppliers to
Airbus and Embraer.

00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:54.210
And so this gets
very complicated.

00:34:54.210 --> 00:34:57.660
OK, so who are the
stakeholders of an enterprise?

00:34:57.660 --> 00:34:59.400
They're any group
or individual who

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.230
can affect or is affected by
the organizational objective.

00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:09.470
So you have your employees,
partners, suppliers, unions,

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:11.090
customers, shareholders.

00:35:11.090 --> 00:35:13.460
These are all stakeholders
who can affect or are

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:16.440
affected by your enterprise.

00:35:16.440 --> 00:35:19.903
Jennifer, at Boston Medical
Center, do you have any--

00:35:19.903 --> 00:35:22.320
I don't know how long you've
been at Boston Medical Center

00:35:22.320 --> 00:35:23.030
and whether you--

00:35:25.565 --> 00:35:28.430
do any of these kind of
things resonate with you

00:35:28.430 --> 00:35:30.763
in terms of who your
stakeholders are there?

00:35:30.763 --> 00:35:31.430
What department?

