00:42:34.670 --> 00:42:37.520
They can ship it in three days.

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:38.840
Floor space reduced.

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:41.090
Production went up and so on.

00:42:41.090 --> 00:42:43.130
Let's just talk about this.

00:42:43.130 --> 00:42:48.960
Kanban, Japanese word, who's
ever heard the word kanban?

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:51.300
One, Catherine has heard kanban.

00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:53.460
Kind of a strange
word, isn't it?

00:42:53.460 --> 00:42:57.840
How many of you at home
keep a shopping list?

00:42:57.840 --> 00:43:00.150
OK, so tell me.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:03.360
How do you make your
shopping list, Whitney?

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:05.825
AUDIENCE: Like in
terms of which ones?

00:43:05.825 --> 00:43:07.450
Well, now, I use an
app for everything.

00:43:07.450 --> 00:43:09.082
So I don't [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:09.082 --> 00:43:11.410
On the weekends,
we'll kind of pick

00:43:11.410 --> 00:43:12.790
what things I'm going to do.

00:43:12.790 --> 00:43:14.230
And it forms a list for me.

00:43:14.230 --> 00:43:16.350
So I carry it around
with me everywhere.

00:43:16.350 --> 00:43:19.290
EARLL MURMAN: So how do you
make that list of things you--

00:43:19.290 --> 00:43:20.958
well, let's say
grocery shopping, just

00:43:20.958 --> 00:43:21.750
to take an example.

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.210
So grocery shopping, what
do you put on your list?

00:43:24.210 --> 00:43:27.210
AUDIENCE: I pick the recipes,
and it creates a list for me.

00:43:27.210 --> 00:43:28.260
EARLL MURMAN: OK, so
you pick what you need.

00:43:28.260 --> 00:43:28.885
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:28.885 --> 00:43:30.180
EARLL MURMAN: OK, anybody else?

00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:32.433
How do you do your
shopping list, Tony?

00:43:32.433 --> 00:43:33.600
AUDIENCE: I go to my fridge.

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:38.520
And I look at what is
missing I go to my cupboard

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:40.058
and see if there
are things that are

00:43:40.058 --> 00:43:41.350
missing that I need to replace.

00:43:41.350 --> 00:43:43.020
And I write down the list.

00:43:43.020 --> 00:43:44.700
EARLL MURMAN: So
he's got 5S working.

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:47.158
He can look at his cupboard
and see he's missing something,

00:43:47.158 --> 00:43:47.700
right?

00:43:47.700 --> 00:43:49.740
OK, you have some kind of
standardized way of storing

00:43:49.740 --> 00:43:50.550
things in your cupboard.

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:51.000
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:52.320
EARLL MURMAN: OK, and you
spot what you're missing,

00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:54.200
and you put it on
your list again.

00:43:54.200 --> 00:43:55.140
Those are kanbans.

00:43:55.140 --> 00:43:58.830
OK, kanban is nothing more
than a queuing system,

00:43:58.830 --> 00:44:01.020
a visual system,
to indicate what

00:44:01.020 --> 00:44:03.750
material parts or
other information you

00:44:03.750 --> 00:44:07.272
need to keep going.

00:44:07.272 --> 00:44:08.980
In a factory environment,
typically, it's

00:44:08.980 --> 00:44:12.400
a card, a barcoded
card of some kind.

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:19.390
And, at some station where
they're manufacturing something

00:44:19.390 --> 00:44:20.830
or, in a health
care environment,

00:44:20.830 --> 00:44:25.860
where they need some supplies,
they need more of that.

00:44:25.860 --> 00:44:27.900
And so they make
a little system.

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:29.600
And then someone delivers it.

00:44:29.600 --> 00:44:33.590
OK, now, the
opposite is, instead

00:44:33.590 --> 00:44:35.527
of deciding what
recipes you have

00:44:35.527 --> 00:44:37.610
and what you're going to
buy, you go to the store,

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:39.110
and you say, oh,
this is on special.

00:44:39.110 --> 00:44:42.440
I'm going to load up on
whatever, hamburger or toilet

00:44:42.440 --> 00:44:44.000
paper or ketchup.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:45.583
OK, what you're doing
is you're buying

00:44:45.583 --> 00:44:47.208
because you're getting
volume discount,

00:44:47.208 --> 00:44:48.350
but you may not need it.

00:44:48.350 --> 00:44:50.420
So a kanban system
is one where you only

00:44:50.420 --> 00:44:53.810
deliver what's needed to
whoever is doing the work.

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:57.800
And there's some cue,
usually a visual cue.

00:44:57.800 --> 00:45:00.410
It can be a barcoded card.

00:45:00.410 --> 00:45:05.210
It could be a bin that's empty,
some space on the floor that I

00:45:05.210 --> 00:45:07.100
need a new delivery there.

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:10.100
In an engineering environment
or a work office environment,

00:45:10.100 --> 00:45:12.230
it might be an empty inbox.

00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:15.560
Also, an interesting
kanban I saw,

00:45:15.560 --> 00:45:20.210
this was a factory at McDonnell
Douglas in East St. Louis.

00:45:20.210 --> 00:45:22.850
And they have supplies,
something coming

00:45:22.850 --> 00:45:24.620
from a company in California.

00:45:24.620 --> 00:45:28.730
They make a packaging container
that this product went into.

00:45:28.730 --> 00:45:30.230
And so the company
is in California.

00:45:30.230 --> 00:45:31.730
The factory is in
East St. Louis.

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:35.640
And on the ceiling is
a camera looking down

00:45:35.640 --> 00:45:38.922
at the number of these
boxes that are there.

00:45:38.922 --> 00:45:40.380
And, when the
company in California

00:45:40.380 --> 00:45:43.560
sees they need more
boxes, they ship them.

00:45:43.560 --> 00:45:46.090
That's a kanban.

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:51.350
So Toyota implemented kanban
in their production system.

00:45:51.350 --> 00:45:52.700
It took them 20 years.

00:45:55.310 --> 00:45:57.145
You wouldn't think it
would take that long.

00:45:57.145 --> 00:45:58.520
When they first
started doing it,

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:00.145
they actually came
to the United States

00:46:00.145 --> 00:46:01.400
and saw the supermarkets.

00:46:01.400 --> 00:46:04.700
And, in the supermarket,
the potato chips,

00:46:04.700 --> 00:46:06.740
you buy potato chips, and
the shelf looks empty.

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:08.315
So the potato chip
guy comes and sees

00:46:08.315 --> 00:46:09.440
you need more potato chips.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:11.793
That's where it came
from, supermarkets.

00:46:11.793 --> 00:46:12.710
So they introduced it.

00:46:12.710 --> 00:46:14.480
It took them 10 years after
they did the experiments

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:16.813
to make it across the whole
company and another 10 years

00:46:16.813 --> 00:46:18.830
to make it across
their suppliers.

00:46:18.830 --> 00:46:21.020
OK, and they continued
to work on it.

