That's good, some reds.

00:47:07.850 --> 00:47:10.730
OK, so it's going to
take a little while.

00:47:10.730 --> 00:47:12.495
Maybe it looks like,
I'd say, the bulk

00:47:12.495 --> 00:47:14.370
of the numbers I have
up here are five years.

00:47:14.370 --> 00:47:17.690
Susan, you work with a lot
of health care organizations.

00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:20.210
You said you've been
doing this for five years.

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:24.150
What kind of-- how long are you
seeing that a typical health

00:47:24.150 --> 00:47:25.330
care organization--

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:26.788
SUSAN SHEEHY: Most
of the hospitals

00:47:26.788 --> 00:47:29.310
we've worked with take at
least five years if not more

00:47:29.310 --> 00:47:30.810
because you really
have to spread it

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:32.012
throughout the organization.

00:47:32.012 --> 00:47:32.970
And it takes that long.

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:36.305
You can't just teach five
people and say, OK, we're lean.

00:47:36.305 --> 00:47:38.370
So it's at least five
years if not more.

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:39.930
And that's with
an all-out effort.

00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:41.305
EARLL MURMAN: At
least five years

00:47:41.305 --> 00:47:45.660
with an all-out effort,
not a half-hearted effort.

00:47:45.660 --> 00:47:48.390
OK, so this is a big
commitment for an organization

00:47:48.390 --> 00:47:49.240
to implement lean.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:52.890
OK, they're not going to see
quarterly bottom-line profit

00:47:52.890 --> 00:47:55.050
changes, which their
shareholders may

00:47:55.050 --> 00:47:56.660
be looking for.

00:47:56.660 --> 00:47:59.870
What are some questions that
this introductory module

00:47:59.870 --> 00:48:01.590
kind of brings up in your mind?

00:48:01.590 --> 00:48:04.910
Or do you have comments you'd
like to make or suggestions?

00:48:04.910 --> 00:48:06.500
Yeah, Jennifer.

00:48:06.500 --> 00:48:08.780
AUDIENCE: For the
6S activity, if you

00:48:08.780 --> 00:48:11.930
had asked me to sort that
stuff from the very beginning,

00:48:11.930 --> 00:48:14.780
I probably would have
ended up on the end page

00:48:14.780 --> 00:48:17.115
first with everything in--

00:48:17.115 --> 00:48:18.760
if you just said
sort these things,

00:48:18.760 --> 00:48:20.638
it would have been
super subselected,

00:48:20.638 --> 00:48:22.430
which might just be my
own personality when

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:23.570
somebody says sort.

00:48:23.570 --> 00:48:27.230
So I'm a little unclear what
the difference between sort,

00:48:27.230 --> 00:48:30.280
standard, straighten,
and standardize

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:31.113
are in that respect.

00:48:31.113 --> 00:48:32.655
EARLL MURMAN: That's
a good question.

00:48:32.655 --> 00:48:35.040
You know, I think the sort
one is, first of all, just

00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:38.010
get rid of stuff that
shouldn't be there.

00:48:38.010 --> 00:48:41.910
And I have slides from a
lot of different examples

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:46.290
of storerooms that had totally
obsolete equipment in them.

00:48:46.290 --> 00:48:48.990
And people were
spending lots of time

00:48:48.990 --> 00:48:50.953
looking for something
that was not

00:48:50.953 --> 00:48:52.120
all that obsolete equipment.

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:53.910
So I think the sort
part is pretty quick.

00:48:53.910 --> 00:48:56.820
Now, the straighten
and standardize I think

00:48:56.820 --> 00:49:00.240
might be done as a single step.

00:49:00.240 --> 00:49:03.330
But I'm not going to--

00:49:03.330 --> 00:49:04.350
I think you're fine.

00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:05.340
It's a good comment.

00:49:05.340 --> 00:49:07.860
But what's amazing
to me is how often

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:10.493
an organization starts with 5S.

00:49:10.493 --> 00:49:11.910
I mean, you would
think, why isn't

00:49:11.910 --> 00:49:13.473
anybody doing it this way?

00:49:13.473 --> 00:49:14.640
SUSAN SHEEHY: It's because--

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:16.098
and we hear this
term all the time.

00:49:16.098 --> 00:49:17.805
It's the way we've
always done it.

00:49:17.805 --> 00:49:18.930
That's what we always hear.

00:49:18.930 --> 00:49:20.388
Because it's the
way we've always--

00:49:20.388 --> 00:49:22.860
and workarounds
and do-overs have

00:49:22.860 --> 00:49:24.160
been built into the system.

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:27.360
So nobody even recognizes
that they're doing it.

00:49:27.360 --> 00:49:29.550
It just becomes part
of the daily work.

00:49:29.550 --> 00:49:30.600
EARLL MURMAN: Do you
have a question, Monica?

00:49:30.600 --> 00:49:32.142
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
was just wondering.

00:49:32.142 --> 00:49:34.540
You said that the average
time was five years.

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:38.010
So I was just wondering, in our
culture of immediate response

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:41.600
time and response to
crisis, how do you sustain

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:43.020
an organization's interest--

00:49:43.020 --> 00:49:44.020
EARLL MURMAN: That's a--

00:49:44.020 --> 00:49:45.145
AUDIENCE: --for five years?

00:49:45.145 --> 00:49:48.620
EARLL MURMAN:
--really good question

00:49:48.620 --> 00:49:49.820
I'll answer what I can.

00:49:49.820 --> 00:49:53.120
And Bo and Sue and
others can pipe in.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:55.550
First of all, you have to
have this so-called burning

00:49:55.550 --> 00:49:56.540
platform.

00:49:56.540 --> 00:49:58.430
That is there's sort
of no other option.

00:49:58.430 --> 00:50:01.200
Either we do it, or
we go out of business.

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:02.870
So it's very hard
for an organization

00:50:02.870 --> 00:50:07.100
that's doing extremely well
to adopt something like this.

00:50:09.820 --> 00:50:12.995
Secondly, it takes leadership.

00:50:12.995 --> 00:50:18.013
It has to be that the
organizational leadership says,

00:50:18.013 --> 00:50:19.430
this is important,
and we're going

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:22.390
to have constancy of
purpose and sustain this.

00:50:22.390 --> 00:50:25.077
We're going to start this
and do it and stay with it.

00:50:25.077 --> 00:50:27.160
And then, third, it has
to align with the strategy

00:50:27.160 --> 00:50:28.145
of the organization.

00:50:28.145 --> 00:50:30.770
That is it has to be built into
what the organization is trying

00:50:30.770 --> 00:50:31.270
to do.

00:50:31.270 --> 00:50:32.690
It can't be something separate.

00:50:32.690 --> 00:50:33.950
We're trying to do
this, and, meanwhile,

00:50:33.950 --> 00:50:35.180
we're going to do lean.

00:50:35.180 --> 00:50:37.080
The two have to be together.

00:50:37.080 --> 00:50:42.157
And, frankly, many
organizations can't do it.

00:50:42.157 --> 00:50:43.740
SUSAN SHEEHY: I could
answer that too.

00:50:43.740 --> 00:50:46.540
It's also a series of
incremental changes.

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:48.390
So, if something happens,
like a medication

00:50:48.390 --> 00:50:51.450
error that's disastrous, you
can certainly start with that.

00:50:51.450 --> 00:50:54.060
And, as you have
improvements, you

00:50:54.060 --> 00:50:57.660
celebrate those improvements
and distribute that information

00:50:57.660 --> 00:51:00.630
so that it's a
continuous improvement.

00:51:00.630 --> 00:51:03.750
And it can happen over time with
really good things happening

00:51:03.750 --> 00:51:04.980
along the way.

00:51:04.980 --> 00:51:08.470
But to roll it out to an entire
organization takes a long time.

00:51:08.470 --> 00:51:10.470
But we tell people we
have to start somewhere.

00:51:10.470 --> 00:51:13.290
And it's not like it's going to
alter your whole organization

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:14.130
overnight.

00:51:14.130 --> 00:51:17.430
It's celebrating those
incremental things that you do,

00:51:17.430 --> 00:51:19.860
looking at your data,
looking at your outcomes,

00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:23.070
looking at your staff
turnover, and using

00:51:23.070 --> 00:51:25.420
that to build your lean program.

00:51:25.420 --> 00:51:29.145
So it takes time, but you can
celebrate things along the way.

00:51:29.145 --> 00:51:30.270
EARLL MURMAN: The biggest--

00:51:30.270 --> 00:51:35.440
I think the biggest
barrier to this

00:51:35.440 --> 00:51:38.230
is if there's a change in
the leadership at the top,

00:51:38.230 --> 00:51:41.000
and the new person doesn't
really understand it.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:44.820
And then the whole
thing can crash.

00:51:44.820 --> 00:51:45.480
Bo?

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:47.272
BO MADSEN: I think, as
well, it's important

00:51:47.272 --> 00:51:50.040
that you have a vision, that
your organization has a vision,

00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:53.520
and that everybody knows
what that vision is.

00:51:53.520 --> 00:51:55.770
And then the beginning
is the hardest,

00:51:55.770 --> 00:52:00.660
but, in reality, we all
want to do value-added work.

00:52:00.660 --> 00:52:03.510
We want to do the work that
we're actually employed to do.

00:52:03.510 --> 00:52:05.190
People, they enjoy that.

00:52:05.190 --> 00:52:09.600
When they can see with the
first steps that the waste

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:12.750
that we're sucked into every
day, that that goes away

00:52:12.750 --> 00:52:14.970
and you're more
productive, that's nice.

00:52:14.970 --> 00:52:17.230
People, they enjoy that.

00:52:17.230 --> 00:52:19.230
EARLL MURMAN: Good, what
are some questions that

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:23.190
come from the
engineering folks here?

00:52:23.190 --> 00:52:24.727
Yeah?

00:52:24.727 --> 00:52:27.060
AUDIENCE: So, at some point,
you pointed out a disparity

00:52:27.060 --> 00:52:31.380
between how many hours of
training both United States

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:34.460
and Japanese companies,
exactly, give to their workers.

00:52:34.460 --> 00:52:37.950
And this might be
silly, but it seems

00:52:37.950 --> 00:52:41.648
that the people are what pretty
much makes the company run.

00:52:41.648 --> 00:52:46.820
So, if they're spending so much
time training their workers

00:52:46.820 --> 00:52:49.800
and getting so much
profit off of it,

00:52:49.800 --> 00:52:53.750
how are we not doing
the same thing?

00:52:53.750 --> 00:52:55.270
EARLL MURMAN: So
is the question--

00:52:55.270 --> 00:52:57.157
is the question, does
the training detract

00:52:57.157 --> 00:52:58.490
from the productive [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:00.940
AUDIENCE: No, my question is,
why aren't we investing more

00:53:00.940 --> 00:53:02.185
into training our workers?

00:53:02.185 --> 00:53:06.720
EARLL MURMAN: Oh yeah, so that's
been a real change in the US

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:09.300
companies as they've
adopted these

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:11.760
is they've come to realize
the importance of training.

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:14.670
And they do invest
a lot in training.

00:53:14.670 --> 00:53:17.130
A typical company that
I know of in the US

00:53:17.130 --> 00:53:19.800
will invest at least 40 hours
a week for every employee

00:53:19.800 --> 00:53:21.810
to be trained during the year.

00:53:21.810 --> 00:53:24.090
And training can be broad.

00:53:24.090 --> 00:53:26.280
It can be specific to
that particular job,

00:53:26.280 --> 00:53:28.830
but it could be much broader,
just communication skills

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:33.900
or sometimes even just
awareness about their culture

00:53:33.900 --> 00:53:35.530
of the customers
in other countries.

00:53:35.530 --> 00:53:37.530
AUDIENCE: So do you think
that the difference is

00:53:37.530 --> 00:53:42.773
not in training hours anymore,
but in the workers themselves?

00:53:42.773 --> 00:53:44.190
EARLL MURMAN: I
really don't know.

00:53:44.190 --> 00:53:45.030
I'm not sure I can answer that.

00:53:45.030 --> 00:53:46.410
I can say that they
are investing more

00:53:46.410 --> 00:53:47.350
in training hours.

00:53:47.350 --> 00:53:50.250
Whether it's because the workers
are different, I don't know.

00:53:50.250 --> 00:53:50.910
Yeah.

00:53:50.910 --> 00:53:53.337
There may be a chicken
and egg situation there.

00:53:53.337 --> 00:53:55.170
One question here, and
then we'll come back.

00:53:55.170 --> 00:53:59.250
AUDIENCE: OK, so you mentioned
that a lean enterprise creates

00:53:59.250 --> 00:54:01.210
value to multiple stakeholders.

00:54:01.210 --> 00:54:02.750
EARLL MURMAN: Yeah.

00:54:02.750 --> 00:54:04.890
AUDIENCE: But what happens
if those values are not

00:54:04.890 --> 00:54:05.840
necessarily aligned?

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:07.007
EARLL MURMAN: Aligned.

00:54:07.007 --> 00:54:07.590
Good question.

00:54:07.590 --> 00:54:09.260
AUDIENCE: I'm
thinking, sometimes,

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:10.465
you have the shareholders.

00:54:10.465 --> 00:54:13.610
And they might be willing to
move the enterprise-- transform

00:54:13.610 --> 00:54:15.610
the enterprise in one direction.

00:54:15.610 --> 00:54:17.630
And you can have the employees.

00:54:17.630 --> 00:54:19.550
They don't want
change because they're

00:54:19.550 --> 00:54:21.108
comfortable in that situation.

00:54:21.108 --> 00:54:21.650
I don't know.

00:54:21.650 --> 00:54:23.720
EARLL MURMAN: No,
it's a great question.

00:54:23.720 --> 00:54:24.519
Is it Matthias?

00:54:24.519 --> 00:54:25.144
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:54:25.144 --> 00:54:29.610
EARLL MURMAN: Matthias
asked is the shareholders

00:54:29.610 --> 00:54:31.635
values are not always--

00:54:31.635 --> 00:54:34.270
will normally not be
aligned completely.

00:54:34.270 --> 00:54:36.690
OK, so you have to
do the best you can.

00:54:36.690 --> 00:54:39.820
OK, I mean, you have
to find something.

00:54:39.820 --> 00:54:41.820
I mean, the ideal is if
you could find something

00:54:41.820 --> 00:54:43.988
where every stakeholder
gains something.

00:54:43.988 --> 00:54:45.780
Maybe they don't gain
everything they want,

00:54:45.780 --> 00:54:46.780
but they gain something.

00:54:46.780 --> 00:54:48.570
Something is better than before.

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:50.310
OK, so let me take
the employee thing.

00:54:55.020 --> 00:54:56.280
I think one of the--

00:54:56.280 --> 00:54:58.670
I think the question Monica
asked relates to that too.

00:54:58.670 --> 00:55:02.820
One of the things
that-- one of the things

00:55:02.820 --> 00:55:05.967
that successful organizations
do that implement lean is they

00:55:05.967 --> 00:55:07.800
make it known to their
employees that nobody

00:55:07.800 --> 00:55:10.380
is going to lose their
job because of increase

00:55:10.380 --> 00:55:12.590
in productivity.

00:55:12.590 --> 00:55:14.850
So it's very hard if you
go into an organization

00:55:14.850 --> 00:55:17.698
and say, Emily, I want
you to help improve us.

00:55:17.698 --> 00:55:19.490
And, by the way, we
probably won't need you

00:55:19.490 --> 00:55:20.930
when we're finished.

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:23.390
Your heart is not
going to be in that.

00:55:23.390 --> 00:55:27.390
So instead, you
say, Emily, we want

00:55:27.390 --> 00:55:29.373
to have a better organization.

00:55:29.373 --> 00:55:30.790
And you're going
to be part of it.

00:55:30.790 --> 00:55:32.970
You may not be doing the same
thing you were doing before.

00:55:32.970 --> 00:55:34.887
We may have to train you
to do something else,

00:55:34.887 --> 00:55:37.140
or we may have to do something.

00:55:37.140 --> 00:55:39.440
But you're valuable to
us, and we want you here.

00:55:39.440 --> 00:55:40.920
And we want you to
help us improve.

00:55:40.920 --> 00:55:43.710
So Emily is going to come out.

00:55:43.710 --> 00:55:45.290
She'll probably be
happier when she's

00:55:45.290 --> 00:55:47.040
done because she's
probably not completely

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:48.538
satisfied with her job.

00:55:48.538 --> 00:55:49.830
And they'll be more productive.

00:55:49.830 --> 00:55:52.830
And maybe they'll end
up outsourcing stuff,

00:55:52.830 --> 00:55:55.960
but they'll find a place for
Emily in the organization.

00:55:55.960 --> 00:55:59.830
So you want to make sure it's
as much of a win-win as you can.

00:55:59.830 --> 00:56:00.900
And that's the challenge.

00:56:00.900 --> 00:56:07.130
I mean, sometimes, it's hard.

00:56:07.130 --> 00:56:10.790
And, unfortunately,
the short-term focus

00:56:10.790 --> 00:56:15.243
of our financial
system is a barrier

00:56:15.243 --> 00:56:16.910
for some of these
long-term commitments.

00:56:16.910 --> 00:56:19.890
So it takes a lot of strong
leadership to overcome that.

00:56:19.890 --> 00:56:20.700
And I think Susan--

00:56:20.700 --> 00:56:21.200
good.

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:23.983
You want to show
incremental improvement.

00:56:23.983 --> 00:56:26.150
You want to try to get
better and better and better,

00:56:26.150 --> 00:56:27.360
not [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:29.780
SUSAN SHEEHY: But I also think
that the equation in health

00:56:29.780 --> 00:56:33.290
care traditionally has been that
employees were on the expense

00:56:33.290 --> 00:56:35.310
side of the equation.

00:56:35.310 --> 00:56:39.020
And so, when they needed to
cut costs, they cut positions.

00:56:39.020 --> 00:56:41.780
And what Toyota does
is their employees

00:56:41.780 --> 00:56:44.310
are on the value
side of the equation.

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:46.670
And so they value
those employees.

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:49.862
And that makes the difference
in the expense side as well.

00:56:49.862 --> 00:56:51.320
And I think that
makes a difference

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:54.980
because Toyota expects their
employees to make suggestions.

00:56:54.980 --> 00:56:56.545
And they implement
their suggestions

00:56:56.545 --> 00:56:57.920
where, in health
care, we haven't

00:56:57.920 --> 00:56:59.870
done a good job at doing that.

00:56:59.870 --> 00:57:02.000
Employees were just employees.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.580
And now we're starting
to see that employees are

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:05.960
the experts at what they do.

00:57:05.960 --> 00:57:07.710
And so we need to start
listening to them.

00:57:07.710 --> 00:57:09.740
And I have an example.

00:57:09.740 --> 00:57:12.530
I was doing work at a small
rural hospital in northern New

00:57:12.530 --> 00:57:14.570
England, a 50-bed hospital.

00:57:14.570 --> 00:57:18.140
And this class, I did
two classes of 16 people.

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:21.650
And they were working on some
productivity kinds of issues.

00:57:21.650 --> 00:57:24.510
And they came up with
$3 million in savings

00:57:24.510 --> 00:57:28.870
from the delayed OR start times
and canceled imaging tests

00:57:28.870 --> 00:57:30.120
and all those kinds of things.

00:57:30.120 --> 00:57:32.930
And they really did a beautiful
job with their projects.

00:57:32.930 --> 00:57:36.080
And the last day at report
out, the CEO was there.

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:37.080
He didn't hire us.

00:57:37.080 --> 00:57:39.450
It was a grant
through the state.

00:57:39.450 --> 00:57:42.030
So they did this report out and
talked about what they found.

00:57:42.030 --> 00:57:46.340
And, at the end, he said,
this really makes me look bad.

00:57:46.340 --> 00:57:47.580
And I said, excuse me.

00:57:47.580 --> 00:57:50.840
And he said, I should
have fixed these things.

00:57:50.840 --> 00:57:52.550
[INAUDIBLE]

00:57:52.550 --> 00:57:55.430
It was just-- it was the
old, traditional model

00:57:55.430 --> 00:57:56.480
of the hierarchy.

00:57:56.480 --> 00:57:58.550
I tell you what to
do, and you do it.

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:00.560
If I tell you to cut
10% off your budget,

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:04.130
you do it, not show me
how you can increase

00:58:04.130 --> 00:58:05.850
throughput and revenue.

00:58:05.850 --> 00:58:08.430
So we need to just change
our thinking in health care.

00:58:08.430 --> 00:58:10.970
And it's happening,
but very slowly.

00:58:10.970 --> 00:58:14.030
And valuing the employee
is the most important thing

00:58:14.030 --> 00:58:15.350
we need to do.

00:58:15.350 --> 00:58:17.690
And, unfortunately,
the term lean

00:58:17.690 --> 00:58:20.090
gives people the
absolute fear that we're

00:58:20.090 --> 00:58:21.590
going to cut positions.

00:58:21.590 --> 00:58:23.240
That's what they
immediately think

00:58:23.240 --> 00:58:25.800
when you say we're coming
in to do lean, that word.

00:58:25.800 --> 00:58:27.800
EARLL MURMAN: Do that,
and lean became the word.

00:58:27.800 --> 00:58:28.220
It's like the--

00:58:28.220 --> 00:58:29.137
SUSAN SHEEHY: Exactly.

00:58:29.137 --> 00:58:31.040
EARLL MURMAN: It's
like the evolution

00:58:31.040 --> 00:58:32.150
of industry I showed you.

00:58:32.150 --> 00:58:33.530
We can't change the word now.

00:58:33.530 --> 00:58:34.790
It's just become part of it.

00:58:34.790 --> 00:58:36.248
SUSAN SHEEHY: It's
just what it is.

00:58:36.248 --> 00:58:38.840
EARLL MURMAN: It came actually
from a MIT graduate student

00:58:38.840 --> 00:58:40.820
in a research
seminar one day when

00:58:40.820 --> 00:58:42.710
they were talking
about the things they

00:58:42.710 --> 00:58:46.340
were learning about the
Japanese automotive industry.

00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:48.360
And they said, what are
we going to call this?

00:58:48.360 --> 00:58:50.120
And he said, well, let's call
it lean because we're doing

00:58:50.120 --> 00:58:51.650
more with less, and it stuck.

00:58:51.650 --> 00:58:53.960
But it unfortunately has
a negative sound to it,

00:58:53.960 --> 00:58:55.767
lean and mean and all
that kind of stuff.

00:58:55.767 --> 00:58:57.350
So we have time for
one more question.

00:58:57.350 --> 00:58:58.845
Did you have a question?

00:58:58.845 --> 00:59:01.220
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so I'm going
to play the skeptical a bit.

00:59:01.220 --> 00:59:06.380
How do you establish causation
between these methods

00:59:06.380 --> 00:59:07.580
and the outcome?

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:09.500
How is it not just
an improvement

00:59:09.500 --> 00:59:10.870
in employee mentality?

00:59:10.870 --> 00:59:14.067
I want to have this company
that won't just sit back and--

00:59:14.067 --> 00:59:15.900
EARLL MURMAN: That's a
really good question.

00:59:15.900 --> 00:59:18.110
How can we show that the
kind of results we showed

00:59:18.110 --> 00:59:19.617
here come from lean?

00:59:19.617 --> 00:59:21.950
Because there are a lot of
confounding factors going on.

00:59:21.950 --> 00:59:23.617
There's a changing
business environment.

00:59:23.617 --> 00:59:25.310
There may be other
things going on.

00:59:25.310 --> 00:59:30.200
And I guess, in a
scientific sense,

00:59:30.200 --> 00:59:32.290
it might be very
hard to do that.

00:59:32.290 --> 00:59:36.570
But, when you go and look at
organization after organization

00:59:36.570 --> 00:59:39.810
after organization that adopts
this and sees improvement,

00:59:39.810 --> 00:59:43.410
there's a correlation there
that adopting lean thinking

00:59:43.410 --> 00:59:46.170
and the way we teach it here--

00:59:46.170 --> 00:59:49.210
one of the pitfalls in
adopting lean thinking is--

00:59:49.210 --> 00:59:51.400
and let's take the 5S or 6S.

00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:54.210
A lot of people
think lean is a tool.

00:59:54.210 --> 00:59:55.840
Oh OK, now, I know how to do 5S.

00:59:55.840 --> 00:59:56.510
I can fix it.

00:59:56.510 --> 00:59:57.510
That's not what lean is.

00:59:57.510 --> 01:00:00.380
Lean is this change in culture
and the way of thinking

01:00:00.380 --> 01:00:01.450
that Susan mentioned.

01:00:01.450 --> 01:00:04.350
And that takes some time.